<!DOCTYPE MAN SYSTEM "../../man.dtd">
<MAN>
  <LANGUAGE>eng</LANGUAGE>
  <TITLE>hess  </TITLE>
  <TYPE>Scilab Function  </TYPE>
  <DATE>April 1993  </DATE>
  <SHORT_DESCRIPTION name="hess"> Hessenberg form  </SHORT_DESCRIPTION>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>H = hess(A)  </CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>[U,H] = hess(A)  </CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>
  </CALLING_SEQUENCE>
  <PARAM>
 <PARAM_INDENT>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>A  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
    : real or complex square matrix
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>H  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
    : real or complex square matrix
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>U  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
    : orthogonal or unitary square matrix
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
 </PARAM_INDENT>
  </PARAM>
  <DESCRIPTION>
  <P>
    produces a unitary matrix <VERB>U</VERB> and a Hessenberg matrix <VERB>H</VERB> so
    that <VERB>A = U*H*U&apos;</VERB> and <VERB>U&apos;*U</VERB> = Identity.  By itself, <VERB>hess(A)</VERB>
    returns <VERB>H</VERB>.
  </P>
  <P>
    The Hessenberg form of a matrix is zero below the first 
    subdiagonal. If the matrix is symmetric or
    Hermitian, the form is tridiagonal.
  </P>
  </DESCRIPTION>
  <ITEMIZE label='REFERENCES'>
  <P>
  hess function is based on the Lapack routines
 DGEHRD, DORGHR for  real matrices and  ZGEHRD, ZORGHR for the complex case.
  </P>
  </ITEMIZE>
  <EXAMPLE><![CDATA[
A=rand(3,3);[U,H]=hess(A);
and( abs(U*H*U'-A)<1.d-10 )
 ]]></EXAMPLE>
